  <section id="pattern158-origin" class="content-section">
    <h2>Pattern 158 Origin</h2>
    <div class="origin-story">
      <p>The name comes from a puzzle in <em>Myst</em> &mdash; the 1993 point-and-click adventure game that defined a generation of puzzle enthusiasts.</p>
      <p>Near the end of the game, the brothers Sirrus and Achenar whisper a clue: <em>"The final page is in the fireplace... Pattern 158."</em> You find the pattern book in the library, turn to page 158, and enter the pattern on the fireplace grid. The wall rotates to reveal a hidden chamber.</p>
      <p>But here's the twist: the brothers are <em>manipulating</em> you. They're trapped in prison books, and they want you to retrieve their final pages so they can escape. They warn you not to touch the green book &mdash; because inside is their father Atrus, and he knows the truth about their treachery.</p>
      <p><strong>Pattern 158 = the code that reveals both the trap AND the true solution.</strong></p>
      <p>That's how I approach engineering problems. The obvious answer (the red and blue pages) is often a trap. The real solution (the green book) is sitting right next to it &mdash; you have to see through the manipulation to find it. The Myst reference signals pattern-recognition thinking to fellow geeks, while "solutions" keeps it professional for business contexts.</p>
      <p class="domain-note">The domain strategy: <strong>pattern158.solutions</strong> (primary), pattern158.dev (catches developers), pattern158.com (catches default searches). All point to the same portfolio.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
